Intellij has a very useful feature called "[show type info](https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/edit-scala-code.html)" that shows type information for the selected expression. For example, consider the following code:

``` typescript
function fn(count: number, str: string) {
	return str + count;
}
```

In Intellij IDEA it is possible to select `str + count` expression and press `alt + =` and get the result type of the selected expression (`string` in the example).

I think this feature would be very beneficial specially in the languages that type inference is very important. Although I am not sure this repository is the right place to ask for this feature.

### Search Terms
macro , userscripts , greasemonkey

### Requirement
Allow executing user defined javascript functions on code base, just like snippets
Some repeated tasks can be automated using some small scripts, example advanced search/replace for refactoring

API can be a function which takes a `context` object and returns a list of  `Operation` requests, then `vscode` internals can execute that operation.
To keep implementation robust and simple user action cannot have any side effects. Only way to make any changes is returning some `operation` request. 

#### API
```ts
declare function userAction(context: Context): (Promise<Operation>|Operation)[];

interface Context {
    readonly openedFile: string;
    readonly selectedText: string | undefined;
    readonly cursorLine: number;
    readonly cursorColumn: number;
}

type Operation = OperationAddText | OperationOpenFiles | OperationCloseFiles;

interface OperationBase {
    operationType: OperationType
}

const enum OperationType {
    AddText,
    OpenFiles,
    CloseFiles,
}

interface OperationAddText extends OperationBase {
    // adds new text at cusror, If some text is selected then selected text is replaced
    operationType: OperationType.AddText;
    text: string;
}

interface OperationOpenFiles extends OperationBase {
    operationType: OperationType.OpenFiles;
    files: string[];
}

interface OperationCloseFiles extends OperationBase {
    operationType: OperationType.CloseFiles;
    text: string[];
}

```


### Use case
currently we are refactoring a very large code base. While refactoring we encounter same kind of changes, with slightly different syntax, we could write some javascript/typescript to automate this.

